<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n53054l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53054l">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53054l"> 54(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> timeword more / developed than / spaceword</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[It is even less evident that the Verb &mdash; because of its <mark>developed temporal forms</mark> &mdash; is called &lsquo;<mark>timeword</mark>&rsquo; (<i>Zeitwort</i>) in German. The linguistic development might just as well have taken the opposite course, so that, for instance, direction &hellip; would be expressed by means of <mark>spatial forms</mark> of the verb, analogous to our temporal forms.]</font> <small> Fritz Mauthner, <a name="FMBK1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FMBK1"><cite title="source">Beitr&auml;ge zu einer Kritik der Sprache.</cite></a> 3 vols (1901-2) III 37</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
